    FILTER SEMANTICS
    ================
    The `<filter>opened_date&gt;=javascript:gs.daysAgoStart(30)</filter>`
    element uses ServiceNow's encoded-query string format. After XML
    deserialization the platform parser sees the literal string:

        opened_date>=javascript:gs.daysAgoStart(30)

    The semantics are:

      - `opened_date` is the field name on `x_casemgmt_case` (defined in
        ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_opened_date.xml).
      - `>=` is the encoded-query "greater than or equal to" operator.
        The `>` character is reserved in XML and MUST be escaped as
        `&gt;` per XML well-formedness rules (W3C XML 1.0 specification
        section 2.4 "Character Data and Markup"). The literal value
        held inside the `<filter>` text node is `>=`; only its on-disk
        XML serialization renders the `>` character as `&gt;`.
      - `javascript:` is ServiceNow's encoded-query "dynamic value"
        prefix. The platform recognizes the `javascript:` scheme and
        invokes the right-hand-side expression as a server-side script
        at query-execution time. The result of the script is then
        substituted into the comparison.
      - `gs.daysAgoStart(30)` is the GlideSystem helper that returns
        a `GlideDateTime` representing the START of the day (i.e.,
        00:00:00 in the system timezone) that is exactly 30 days
        before "today". This is the ServiceNow-canonical "rolling
        N-day window" idiom and matches AAP Section 0.5.1's filter
        specification verbatim.

    Time-window edge cases:
      - A case with `opened_date` exactly at midnight 30 days ago IS
        included (the comparison is inclusive: `>=`).
      - A case with `opened_date` 30 days and 1 second ago is NOT
        included.
      - A case with `opened_date` 31 days ago is NOT included.
      - A case with `opened_date` "now" IS included.
      - A case with `opened_date` in the future (e.g., a backdated-but-
        forward-pointed seed value) IS included.
      - A case with NULL `opened_date` is NOT included (encoded-query
        comparisons return false for NULL operands).

    AGGREGATION SEMANTICS
    =====================
    The combination of `<aggregate>COUNT</aggregate>`,
    `<aggregation_source/>` (empty), `<group_by/>` (empty), and
    `<type>single_score</type>` produces the SQL-equivalent:

        SELECT COUNT(*)
        FROM   x_casemgmt_case
        WHERE  opened_date >= <gs.daysAgoStart(30) at query time>

    The result is a single non-negative integer. Single-score reports
    do NOT group; they collapse the entire filtered population to one
    scalar value. If a `<group_by>` were specified, the platform would
    attempt to render a chart instead of a single number - hence
    `<group_by/>` is intentionally empty.

    The `<aggregation_source/>` element is empty because COUNT does
    not require a column to count over - it counts rows. AVG / SUM /
    MIN / MAX aggregations require a numeric `<aggregation_source>`,
    but COUNT does not. This matches the agent-prompt's Rule 5
    ("Single-Score Aggregation") verbatim.

    Why type=single_score and not bar/list (per agent prompt insight #3):
    AAP Section 0.4.4 Manager View widget inventory specifies
    "single-score widget for 'Cases opened in last 30 days'." The
    single-score widget renders one large number - the conventional KPI
    presentation for a leading-edge volume indicator. A list would show
    rows of individual cases (cluttering a manager-level dashboard with
    operational detail not relevant to the volume metric); a bar chart
    would require a `<group_by>` (e.g., by day) which would change the
    semantic from "current 30-day total" to "daily breakdown over 30
    days" - a different KPI entirely.

    Why is_real_time=false (per agent prompt insight #5):
    The count changes by at most a few units per day (one increment
    per case opened, one decrement per day as the rolling window
    shifts). Sub-minute freshness is unnecessary for a manager-level
    KPI and would burn PDI resource budget. Setting `is_real_time` to
    false makes the platform compute the score on dashboard load
    (on-demand), which is the appropriate cadence for this metric and
    matches the sibling report convention (avg_time_to_close, my_open_cases,
    my_overdue_tasks all use is_real_time=false).

    DASHBOARD CONSUMPTION
    =====================
    The Manager View dashboard widget (in
    ../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_casemgmt_manager_view.xml) references
    THIS record by `name`:
      <widget>
        <report_name>x_casemgmt_cases_opened_30d</report_name>
        ...
      </widget>
    NO sys_id reference - per AAP Section 0.7.2 "No-hardcoded-sys_id
    constraint" verbatim. The dashboard renders the single-score widget
    using the platform's native single-score-tile component.

    SEED DATA EXPECTATIONS
    ======================
    For the report to display a non-zero meaningful number on the live
    PDI, the ../seed-data/cases/ folder MUST include at least one demo
    case whose `opened_date` falls within the 30-day window (i.e., the
    `opened_date` is between [today minus 30 days at midnight] and
    "now"). Per AAP Section 0.4.1 directory enumeration, the 10 demo
    cases include records spanning all six statuses and both case types;
    the seed-data agent SHOULD set realistic `opened_date` values
    within the recent past (e.g., 1-25 days ago) for at least most of
    the 10 demo cases so this widget renders a meaningful number on
    initial dashboard load.

    NOTE FOR THE SEED-DATA AGENT (per agent prompt validation gate
    block): if seed `opened_date` values are pinned to a specific past
    date for reproducibility, ensure that date is within 30 days of
    expected install time, OR document a re-seed step in
    ../scripts/seed_demo_data.js / ../scripts/round_trip_verify.md.
    The auto-set business rule
    ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_set_opened_date.xml ensures any seed
    case lacking an explicit `opened_date` value will be set to
    `gs.nowDateTime()` at insert - which automatically falls within
    the 30-day window for fresh installs.

